"Parmentier F.J.W., Van Der Molen M.K., Van Huissteden J., Karsanaev S.A., Kononov A.V., Suzdalov D.A., Maximov T.C., Dolman A.J.","Longer growing seasons do not increase net carbon uptake in the northeastern Siberian tundra",2011,"Journal of Geophysical Research: Biogeosciences","116","4", G04013,"","",,,10.1029/2011JG001653,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80155130048&partnerID=40&md5=b02a57dfb138e71f245ccb822b9b131a","Department of Hydrology and Geo-environmental Sciences, Faculty of Earth and Life Sciences, VU University Amsterdam, De Boelelaan 1085-1087, Amsterdam, 1081 HV, Netherlands; Department of Earth and Ecosystem Sciences, Division of Physical Geography and Ecosystems Analysis, Lund University, Sölvegatan 12, Lund, SE-223 62, Sweden; Meteorology and Air Quality Group, Wageningen University, Droevendaalsesteeg 4, Wageningen, 6708 PB, Netherlands; BioGeochemical Cycles of Permafrost Ecosystems Laboratory, Institute for Biological Problems of the Cryolithozone, Russian Academy of Sciences, 41 Prospekt Lenina, Yakutsk, 677980, Russian Federation","Parmentier, F.J.W., Department of Hydrology and Geo-environmental Sciences, Faculty of Earth and Life Sciences, VU University Amsterdam, De Boelelaan 1085-1087, Amsterdam, 1081 HV, Netherlands, Department of Earth and Ecosystem Sciences, Division of Physical Geography and Ecosystems Analysis, Lund University, Sölvegatan 12, Lund, SE-223 62, Sweden; Van Der Molen, M.K., Meteorology and Air Quality Group, Wageningen University, Droevendaalsesteeg 4, Wageningen, 6708 PB, Netherlands; Van Huissteden, J., Department of Hydrology and Geo-environmental Sciences, Faculty of Earth and Life Sciences, VU University Amsterdam, De Boelelaan 1085-1087, Amsterdam, 1081 HV, Netherlands; Karsanaev, S.A., BioGeochemical Cycles of Permafrost Ecosystems Laboratory, Institute for Biological Problems of the Cryolithozone, Russian Academy of Sciences, 41 Prospekt Lenina, Yakutsk, 677980, Russian Federation; Kononov, A.V., BioGeochemical Cycles of Permafrost Ecosystems Laboratory, Institute for Biological Problems of the Cryolithozone, Russian Academy of Sciences, 41 Prospekt Lenina, Yakutsk, 677980, Russian Federation; Suzdalov, D.A., BioGeochemical Cycles of Permafrost Ecosystems Laboratory, Institute for Biological Problems of the Cryolithozone, Russian Academy of Sciences, 41 Prospekt Lenina, Yakutsk, 677980, Russian Federation; Maximov, T.C., BioGeochemical Cycles of Permafrost Ecosystems Laboratory, Institute for Biological Problems of the Cryolithozone, Russian Academy of Sciences, 41 Prospekt Lenina, Yakutsk, 677980, Russian Federation; Dolman, A.J., Department of Hydrology and Geo-environmental Sciences, Faculty of Earth and Life Sciences, VU University Amsterdam, De Boelelaan 1085-1087, Amsterdam, 1081 HV, Netherlands","With global warming, snowmelt is occurring earlier and growing seasons are becoming longer around the Arctic. It has been suggested that this would lead to more uptake of carbon due to a lengthening of the period in which plants photosynthesize. To investigate this suggestion, 8 consecutive years of eddy covariance measurements at a northeastern Siberian graminoid tundra site were investigated for patterns in net ecosystem exchange, gross primary production (GPP) and ecosystem respiration (R<inf>eco</inf>). While GPP showed no clear increase with longer growing seasons, it was significantly increased in warmer summers. Due to these warmer temperatures however, the increase in uptake was mostly offset by an increase in R<inf>eco</inf>. Therefore, overall variability in net carbon uptake was low, and no relationship with growing season length was found. Furthermore, the highest net uptake of carbon occurred with the shortest and the coldest growing season. Low uptake of carbon mostly occurred with longer or warmer growing seasons. We thus conclude that the net carbon uptake of this ecosystem is more likely to decrease rather than to increase under a warmer climate. These results contradict previous research that has showed more net carbon uptake with longer growing seasons. We hypothesize that this difference is due to site-specific differences, such as climate type and soil, and that changes in the carbon cycle with longer growing seasons will not be uniform around the Arctic. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"carbon cycle; eddy covariance; global warming; growing season; net ecosystem exchange; net primary production; nutrient uptake; photosynthesis; tundra; Arctic; Siberia",,,,,,"Aubinet, M., Estimates of the annual net carbon and water exchange of forests: The EUROFLUX methodology (2000) Adv. Ecol. Res., 30, pp. 113-175; Aurela, M., Laurila, T., Tuovinen, J.-P., The timing of snow melt controls the annual CO<inf>2</inf> balance in a subarctic fen (2004) Geophysical Research Letters, 31 (16), pp. L161191-L161194. , DOI 10.1029/2004GL020315; Beringer, J., Chapin III, F.S., Thompson, C.C., McGuire, A.D., Surface energy exchanges along a tundra-forest transition and feedbacks to climate (2005) Agricultural and Forest Meteorology, 131 (3-4), pp. 143-161. , DOI 10.1016/j.agrformet.2005.05.006, PII S0168192305001000; Burba, G.G., McDermitt, D.K., Grelle, A., Anderson, D.J., Xu, L., Addressing the influence of instrument surface heat exchange on the measurements of CO<inf>2</inf> flux from open-path gas analyzers (2008) Global Change Biology, 14 (8), pp. 1854-1876. , DOI 10.1111/j.1365-2486.2008.01606.x; Chapin III, F.S., Role of land-surface changes in Arctic summer warming (2005) Science, 310 (5748), pp. 657-660; Churkina, G., Schimel, D., Braswell, B.H., Xiao, X., Spatial analysis of growing season length control over net ecosystem exchange (2005) Global Change Biology, 11 (10), pp. 1777-1787. , DOI 10.1111/j.1365-2486.2005.001012.x; Corradi, C., Kolle, O., Walter, K., Zimov, S.A., Schulze, E.-D., Carbon dioxide and methane exchange of a north-east Siberian tussock tundra (2005) Global Change Biology